How to compile/run: To compile the program, use the command "make zap". In order
to run the program, prove the command line with the executable, "./zap", the
function the program should use, "zap" or "unzap", the input file to compress
or decompress, and the output file where the program should output. 



Data Structures/ADT:
The ADT used in this program was a minimum priority queue. In this program, a
minumum priority queue was used because it automatically sorted the frequency
of each character from each node in the queue as it constructed a Huffman
tree. In order to implement this ADT, a unordered map was 
used. First, the unordered map was used to count the number of times that each
character appears in the text. The use of the unordered map was able to create
nodes that held the frequencies of each character, which were then inserted
into a priority queue to assemble a Huffman tree. The priority queue was used
because its status as a minimum priority queue allowed for the nodes that had
the lowest frequency to be removed from the queue first. In this process,
nodes with higher frequencies were able to be accessed later in the tree's 
construction, resulting in more frequent characters being closer to the root
of the tree. 



Testing: 
I tested the functions in phase one of the assignment by creating unit tests.
Within the unit tests, I had created tests for cases with basic cases, fuller
trees and strings, and empty trees or strings. When testing the main zap
program, I started implementing the encoding function first. As a result, 
to test encoding, I used my output file from encoding as an input file for
the sample zap implementation. From there, I used the diff command on the 
original text and the outputted text to confirm that my encoding function was
accurate. Similarly, after I confirmed my "zap" implementation was complete,
I used a similar process for the "unzap" implementation. In this case, I
had confirmed that my zap implementation had worked and I used it on a text,
followed by the unzap implementation. Finally, with this output file, I used
the diff command again to confirm the decoded text was the same as the 
original. The "bad zap file" edgecase was tested by the "bad_zap_file" given
in the original files. 



